Part 2: The Sovereign Crucible (Practical Execution)
🚨 Pre-Flight Rules:

Environment: RHEL 10 VM.

Hardware: Two unformatted virtual disks attached (10GB and 5GB).

Time Limit: 150 Minutes.

Requirement: The system MUST boot cleanly without intervention at the end.

Task 1: System Baseline & Identity
Interrupt the bootloader, reset the root password to Sovereign10!, and boot successfully.

Set the hostname to alpha-node.sovereign.lan.

Create a group named engineers.

Create users stark and banner. Both must have engineers as a secondary group.

Force the user stark to change their password on the very next login.

Task 2: Advanced Storage Engineering
Create a Volume Group named vg_secure on the 10GB disk with an 8MB physical extent size.

Create a Logical Volume named lv_vault consisting of exactly 200 extents.

Format it with XFS and mount it persistently to /mnt/vault.

Create a 512MB Swap partition on the 5GB disk and mount it persistently.

Task 3: The Restricted Zone
Change the group ownership of /mnt/vault to engineers.

Configure the directory so all new files inherit the engineers group, and users can only delete files they personally own.

Create a file inside /mnt/vault named master_key.txt owned by root.

Using an ACL, grant banner read and write access to master_key.txt, but explicitly deny stark any access to it.

Task 4: The Archive Automation
Find all files in /etc that end in .conf.

Using a single find pipeline, copy them to /mnt/vault/conf_backups/ (create the directory if it doesn't exist).

Schedule a cron job for the root user to run at 2:45 PM on every Friday. The job must run: tar -czvf /root/friday_backup.tar.gz /mnt/vault/conf_backups/

Task 5: SELinux & Firewalld Precision
Install httpd. Configure it to listen on port 8888.

Create a custom document root at /opt/web_data. Edit the Apache config to serve files from this directory instead of /var/www/html.

Create an index.html file in /opt/web_data saying "Crucible Active".

Configure the necessary SELinux port policies and file contexts so the service starts without permission errors.

Permanently open port 8888 in the firewall and start the service persistently.

Task 6: RHEL 10 Native Containerization
Log in as banner.

Pull the nginx image from a public registry.

Using the RHEL 10 standard (Quadlets), configure a rootless container named banner_proxy.

Map port 8080 on the host to port 80 in the container.

Map the host directory /mnt/vault to /usr/share/nginx/html inside the container. Ensure the SELinux context is mapped correctly so the container doesn't get a 403 Forbidden error.

Ensure the container starts via systemd and survives a reboot without banner logging in.

Task 7: The Autofs Bridge
Configure autofs so that accessing the directory /bridge/data automatically mounts the local directory /opt/web_data.

Once your 150 minutes are up, run reboot. If the machine comes back up and your container, web server, and mounts are active, you have survived the Crucible.
